      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Urban planners who are serious about meeting aggressive climate targets view congestion pricing as a necessary, powerful tool, not just a theoretical concept. By directly disincentivizing single-occupancy vehicle use in dense areas, it forces a modal shift toward walking, biking, and mass transit. While critics doubt its effectiveness, the data shows that pricing mechanisms are one of the most effective ways to change ingrained commuting behavior and achieve measurable reductions in urban carbon output.",
      "source": "target",
